	      	<h4 id = "week1">Week 5</h4>
			<p><b>Baby : </b> Your baby resembles a tadpole more than a human, but is growing fast. The circulatory system is beginning to form, and the tiny "heart" will start to beat this week. The heart also looks like a tube, but will soon take on its more like four-chamber form. Around day end of 5th week, the heart will make its first, not yet regular contractions. Gradually, the rhythm will even out, and the little heart will beat at about 100 beats per minute, sending the first blood cells to rest body.Your baby is the size of a sesame seedand the embryo is rapidly growing and developing. It doesn’t look much like a baby yet, more like a semi-translucent C-shaped squiggle, and it havw the beginnings of all its organs, its sex and blood type are known, and we could see where the fingers, eyes, inner and outer ear, and mouth will be. (Not on ultrasound) </p>
			<p>First The neural tube starts forming along the body, and  it will partially close. A group of cells is separating out that will later become the spinal column and the entire nervous system. A bulge at the end of the neural tube will grow into the brain. </p>
			<p>The baby’s internal organs and systems continue to develop like  the thyroid and pancreas, liver, troat, and windpipe, as well as the digestive and urinary tracts. The paired organs (kidneys and lungs) already flank the spinal chord. Future sex cells—eggs in girls, sperm in boys—are being created in the genitals. </p>
			<p>The placenta, which carries nutrients to the embryo and removes waste, shows up around weeks 5 or 6. The baby is already surrounded by amniotic fluid, which provides the safe and best conditions for growth: comfortable temperature, space to move around, and protection from the outside world. At this point, fluid around developonf baby (embryo) is much less so it will vulnerable to influences from teretogenic chemical, some medicine, stress, and infection.</p>

			<p><b>Mom : </b>Good news congratulations.  Now it's time declare . As all report 99 percent sure  to confirmed pregnancy.Even u can see gestational sac on ultrasound.</p>
			<p>Rarely and if your menstrual cycle have delayed periods ovulation happened late so on ultrasound u can see pregnancy that might be delayed conception. At this point you may feel the nausea, fatigue, sleepiness, weakness, perhaps dizziness or headaches. Your body is rapidly started to adapt this new hormonal, physical and mental state. </p>
			<p>Yodue to this hormones  fluctuations which is causes of  your mood swings, and how you feel physically.for example Frequent urination are caused by hormones. Same like runny nose or  bloody discharge from nose is the result of swollen mucous membranes, also an effect of hormonal changes. Almost all female experience engorgement and tenderness in her breasts during this time. </p>
			<p>Week 5 can bring early morning sickness. Its primary symptoms are nausea 1st and most common symptoms.You may didn't like smell specifically food or from kitchen.</p>

			<p><b>Useful information : </b> Statistically 80 to 90 percent pregnant women experience some form of morning sickness. Some only have slight nausea, while others can’t even think of food without throwing up. Doctors don’t know why it is so but as a general rule, the earlier it appears, the worse it will be. </p>
			<p>Early morning sickness occur in form of nausea and vomiting. It can, however, cause more severe symptoms, such as excessive salivation, changes in preference to food tastes, dizziness seen, and very rarely muscle or bronchial spasms, jaundice, and dermatitis also occurs Few pregnant women experience weight loss upto 5% due to excessive nausea and vomiting specifically In response to smell of food and altered taste preference in case of mild morning sickness? That would be nausea up to 5 times a day.</p>
			<p>In moderate case  nausea up to 10 times a day, even not. Related to food intake or smells. You may lose up to 3 kg (6-7 lbs), become dehydrated, and very rarely experience a drop in blood pressure or heart arrhythmias. Rarely, morning sickness can be extremely severe, with continue nausea at every hour or even more frequently, severe dehydration, fever, and loss of 8-10 kg (17-22 lbs). The pregnancy is then at risk, and hospitalization may be necessary. </p>
			<p>Any serious symptoms should be treated by a doctor, but light discomforts can be mitigated with home remedies. First off, make it a habit to take light enjoyable walks or at least regularly let in fresh air. Avoid products heavy in preservatives and dyes, rich fatty foods, spicy foods, simple carbs, soda, and coffee. Keep your servings small and mare frequently eat up to 5-6 times a day. In between, drink plenty of fluids to stay hydrated, including green or herbal teas with permission from your doctor, still you can take mineral water, pulpy fruit juices, or compotes. </p>
			<p>Prepare and take  a small snack like some cheese, carrots, crackers, dried fruit, or nuts. Before getting up in the morning eat some dry food like toast,bread biscuits and than  Get up slowly, and better yet, wait 5-10 minutes before getting up. If the nausea still comes, try to keep down a carrot, piece of sour apple, or lemon wedge, or munch on some nuts or a piece of ginger. </p>
			<p>In most cases morning sickness fades away by week 14, but sometimes it lasts longer. In rare cases this unpleasant condition can plague a woman throughout her pregnancy. When morning sickness is severe, your doctor may prescribe special treatment. </p>

