	      <h4 id = "week2">Week 6</h4>
			<p><b>Baby : </b>By week 6 your fetus looks like a tiny tadpole, a big head and a tail. The embryo, which is 3 mm long, floats freely in amniotic fluid which is aprox 3 to 4 ml you can’t feel it yet. The amniotic sac formed around it which will protect the baby from physical forces right until delivery. </p>
			<P>Very minute and tiny facial features gradually come into focus, where the nose and ears will be, and dimples mark the future eyes and mouth. The optic vesicles, which will later become retinas, start to develop. There are more and more blood vessels, highways for fetal red blood cells. The heart transforms from a tube into a two-chamber organ, with one atrium and one ventricle. Its 110–130 beats per minute can already be heard on an ultrasound.</P>
			<P>By the end of this week the liver, intestines, spleen, and lungs will only grow and develop. The neural tube has closed, the spinal column has formed, and the brain has the beginnings of two hemispheres, complete with folds. These allow the embryo to react to external irritants. </P>
			<P>Rudimentary bone marrow has appeared, along with the thymus, which will be in charge of the immune system, “teaching” T-cells fight infections. Besides the immune system, there is also development in the genitourinary and digestive systems. The intestines already have three loops, and a stomach is starting to develop in the digestive tract.</P>

			<P><b>Mom : </b>U may worries for "No symptoms" yet? </P>
			<p>Don't worry. Many women don't feel anything yet, but for those who do, some early pregnancy symptoms tend to start this week. </p>
			<p><b>Nausea or vomiting : </b>Morning sickness is nausea that can strike at any time of day. It usually starts around 6 weeks of pregnancy and is likely to ease up by the end of the first trimester. </p>
			<p><b>Frequent urge to urination : </b>Needing to bathroom more frequently is among the most common early signs of pregnancy and it usually starts at about 6 weeks</p>
			<p><b>Tender, swollen breasts : </b>Breast tenderness can be one of the earliest symptoms of pregnancy. Increased hormone levels boost blood flow, which may make your breasts feel swollen, sore, tingly, and unusually sensitive to touch. </p>
			<p>For many women, exhaustion is among the first signs of pregnancy. But other women hardly seem to slow down at all. No one knows for sure what causes fatigue in early pregnancy, but it's possible that hormonal changes – like the dramatic rise in progesterone – are at least partly responsible.Indigestion and constipation also common that due to higher progesterone.</p>

			<p><b>#Pregnancy checklist at 6 weeks pregnant </b></p>
			<p>Watch and monitorwhat you eat … and drink. Improve your willpower to healthy food and habits. </p>
			<p>There's lots of misinformation and u get various types opinion on food  about what's safe (or not) to eat and drink during pregnancy. Get the facts from authentic source now on which foods and drinks to avoid. </p>
			<p>Learn about prenatal testing options </p>
			<p>Screening tests use blood samples and ultrasound to help assess your baby's chances of having Down syndrome and other conditions. The results can help you decide whether to have chorionic villus sampling (CVS) or amniocentesis to find out for sure about a potential condition. </p>
			<p>Make sure your workplace is safe </p>
			<p>Some jobs or hobbies can be hazardous to you and your developing baby. If you're routinely exposed to chemicals, heavy metals (like lead or mercury), certain biological agents, or radiation (radiology department), you'll need to make some changes as soon as possible.</p>

