	      	<h4 id = "week3">Week 7</h4>
			<p><b>Baby : </b> The baby continues to grow rapidly.At 7 weeks, a baby is a little more than 1/3 of an inch long (about 1 centimeter).That's about the size of a standard blueberry.The umbilical cord is taking shape. This lifeline connects the baby to the placenta to carry oxygenated blood and nutrients to your baby while taking away waste</p>
			<p>Internal organs and systems continue to develop, as do the limbs, face, and individual facial features. The baby starts to move, wiggling its arms and legs and trying to turn its head. Mom won’t feel these movements yet, since the baby is so small. </p>
			<p>During this week the embryo’s arms and legs get longer. The arms separate into hands, forearms, and upper arms. While they still look like little flippers, they already contain the beginnings of joints. The webbing on the hands starts to divide into fingers. </p>
			<p>The face becomes more and more defined: nostrils are now visible, the upper and lower jaw have formed, and the first teeth are in place. In the digestive system, new additions include the small intestine, rectum, and pancreas, and the liver now has bile ducts. This whole system is covered up by the front wall of the belly. </p>
			<p>The heart has grown and separated into two chambers. It no longer fits in the embryo’s chest and protrudes out of it. There are now rudimentary bronchi in the lungs, which themselves continue to grow. </p>
			<p>The endocrine system is online. The cells that make up the immune system are being actively generated. The adrenal glands, which will later produce stress hormones, have been partially formed. After week 7 mom needs to avoid strong emotions, because the baby can already feel, recognize, and react sharply to them.</p>

			<p><b>Mom : </b>By week 7 your uterus (womb) started enlarging.  Mood swings continue and u may happy to stressed out anxieties and fears may appear. Your body and mind needs more rest and sleep atleast 10 hours. You may experience bouts of nausea or dizziness.  </p>
			<p>The hormonal shoot up sometimes shows up on the skin. You may see red or brown splotches, acne, or an oily sheen. In some cases, pregnant woman  may have discomfort or dull in your lower belly as uterus continues to grow </p>
			<p>There will be minor changes to your body shape due to Hormones cause redistribution of fat tissue, so your body becomes rounder and curvier. Your breasts enlarge, which may be accompanied by tenderness, pins and needles, or a sense of heaviness.</p>
			<p>These are some of the 7 weeks pregnant symptoms you might be experiencing: </p>
			<p><b>1. Headaches: </b>The pregnancy hormones that may be giving you morning sickness can also be responsible for headaches. Headaches during pregnancy can also be triggered by fatigue, hunger, and physical or emotional stress. You could try drinking more water, resting more often, and snacking regularly to prevent headaches. </p>
			<p><b>2. Frequent urination: </b> Increased blood volume and hormonal changes during pregnancy trigger the kidneys to expand and to produce more urine, while your growing uterus also puts extra pressure on your bladder. All of this means you might be running to the bathroom more often. Instead of cutting back on fluids, make an effort to drink plenty. Plus, these tips could help reduce frequent urination during pregnancy and beyond: </p>
			<p>Lean forward while peeing to completely empty your bladderPractice Kegel exercises to strengthen your pelvic floor muscles Avoid carbonated drinks, tea, coffee, chocolates, and spicy foods as these can irritate the bladder Drink less water right before bed to avoid night-time visits to the bathroom, but stay very well-hydrated during the day Sometimes frequent urination can be a sign of a urinary tract infection, so if your urine has blood in it, if you feel a burning sensation while peeing or have a tender lower abdomen, or if you have the urge to pee but only pass a few drops, then consult your doctor immediately. </p>
			<p><b>Acne breakout: </b>You can blame the hormonal changes in your body for the acne outburst on your skin. In the initial few weeks it could result in excessive pimples on your face which is because of the increase in hormones called androgens. Before you use any medications or cosmetics for treating acne, consult your doctor to ensure it is safe for you.</p>
			<p><b>3. Mild pelvic cramping: </b> You might feel a lot pelvic cramping even when you are not able to feel the baby move yet. A lot of activity is going on in your uterus and therefore you might feel little spotting too. There is nothing to get worried as this is very normal. However, if the cramps are more painful than the usual periods pain, you should consult the doctor right away.</p>

			<p><b>Useful information</b></p>
			<p>Your doctor may suggest early pregnancy sonography that Better visualised transvaginally.</p>
			<p>Reasons for this scan.</p>
			<ul>
			<li>Confirming twins or multiple pregnancy.</li>
			<li>Confirming fetal heart beats that is very important when there  is bleeding/spotting per vagina or or pain in abdomen or previous history of miscarriage</li>
			<li>Ruling out an ectopic pregnancy it is a very critical and emergency condition where in embryo implants outside the uterine cavity.And checking out another reproductive organs anatomy like uterine position or  fibroid, cervix, for ovarian cyst or tumors which might causes a complication during pregnancy.</li>
			<li>Dating  scan. To know exact date of pregnancy where the mother didn't know  exact last menstrual period date.In Trans vaginal sonography doctor appreciate  3 very  importance structure.</li>
			</ul>
			<p>1. Gestational sac 2. yolk sac and 3. fetal pole with cardiac (pulsation)activity present </p>

			<p><b>Advice for you : </b>Be active for safe and healthy pregnancy and so Avoid unnecessary rest. Avoid unnecessary food.Can do exercise and yoga.Regular visit to your doctor.Take prenatal vitamins and other medicines prescribed by your doctor.</p>

